<P>I could, with plea&s;ure, expatiate upon the ma&s;terly execution of the Life of DRYDEN, which we have &s;een<NOTE N="7" PLACE="foot">See page 85 of this Volume.</NOTE> was one of John&s;on's literary projects at an early period, and which it is remarkable, that after de&s;i&s;ting from it, from a &s;uppo&s;ed &s;cantine&s;s of materials, he &s;hould, at an advanced age, have performed &s;o amply.</P>
<P>His defence of that great poet again&s;t the illiberal attacks upon him, as if his embracing the Roman Catholick communion had been a time-&s;erving mea&s;ure, is a piece of rea&s;oning at once able and candid. Indeed, Dryden him&s;elf, in his <Q REND="inline">"Hind and Panther,"</Q> hath given &s;uch a picture of his mind, that they who know the anxiety for repo&s;e as to the aweful &s;ubject of our &s;tate beyond the grave, though they may think his opinion ill-founded, mu&s;t think charitably of his &s;entiment.</P>
